05190nam a22007935i 9789048550876DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485508767 a10.1515/97890485508762doi  a(DE-B1597)546132  a(OCoLC)1137842720  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0370302bisacsh04a271.492231 aChristman, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Dynamics of the Early Reformation in their Reformed Augustinian Context /cRobert Christman. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Reformed Augustinians of Lower Germany -- t2. The German Reformed Congregation and its Province of Lower Germany -- t3. The Antwerp Cloister -- t4. The Authorities Respond: Pope and Emperor Seize the Initiative -- t5. Wittenberg's Influence on the Events in Lower Germany -- t6. Reformation Ideas in the Low Countries -- t7. 'Summer is at the door': The Impact of the Executions on Martin Luther -- t8. The Impact of the Executions in the Low Countries -- t9. The Impact of the Executions in the German-Speaking Lands of the Holy Roman Empire -- t10. The Marian Dimension -- t11. The Reformed Augustinians of Lower Germany and the Dynamics of the Early Reformation -- tBibliography -- tAbout the Author -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn July 1, 1523, Johann van den Eschen and Hendrik Voes, two Augustinians friars from Antwerp, were burned on the Grand Plaza in Brussels, thereby becoming the first victims of the Reformation. Despite being well-known, the event barely registers in most Reformation histories. By tracing its origins and examining the impact of the executions on Martin Luther, on the Reformed Augustinian world, and on the early Reformation in the Low Countries and the German speaking lands, this study definitively demonstrates that the burnings were in fact the dénouement of broader trends within Late Medieval Reformed Augustinianism, as well as a watershed in the early Reformation. In doing so, it also reveals the central role played by the Augustinian friars of Lower Germany in shaping both the content and spread of the early Reformation, as well as Wittenberg's influence on the events leading up to these first executions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aHistory. 4aLate Middle Ages & Renaissance. 4aTheology and Religion. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aReformed Augustinians, Reformation, Martin Luther, Low Countries, heresy, martyrs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048550876zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048550876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048550876.jpg  a978-3-11-068955-6  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069629-5  DG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2b2020  a978